04439nam a22006975i 9780691187495DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911874957 a10.1515/97806911874952doi  a(DE-B1597)501922  a(OCoLC)1076453780  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBM713b.S27 2001eb 7aREL0400102bisacsh04a296.4/44/09012231 aSatlow, Michael L., eauthor.10aJewish Marriage in Antiquity /cMichael L. Satlow. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENT -- tABBREVIATIONS AND CONVENTIONS -- tPREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART I. Thinking about Marriage -- tChapter One. WHY MARRY? -- tChapter Two. METAPHOR AND MYTH -- tChapter Three. MARRIAGE AND LAW -- tPART II. Marrying -- tChapter Four. SHREDS OF REAL MARRIAGE -- tChapter Five. MAKING A MATCH -- tChapter Six. ENDOGAMY AND EXOGAMY -- tChapter Seven. CUSTOMS AND RITUALS OF MARRIAGE -- tChapter Eight. IRREGULAR UNIONS -- tPART III. Staying Married -- tChapter Nine. THE ECONOMICS OF MARRIAGE -- tChapter Ten. THE IDEAL MARRIAGE -- tCONCLUSIONS -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tSUBJECT INDEX -- tINDEX OF PREMODERN SOURCES -- tINDEX OF MODERN AUTHORS  aMarriage today might be a highly contested topic, but certainly no more than it was in antiquity. Ancient Jews, like their non-Jewish neighbors, grappled with what have become perennial issues of marriage, from its idealistic definitions to its many practical forms to questions of who should or should not wed. In this book, Michael Satlow offers the first in-depth synthetic study of Jewish marriage in antiquity, from ca. 500 B.C.E. to 614 C.E. Placing Jewish marriage in its cultural milieu, Satlow investigates whether there was anything essentially "Jewish" about the institution as it was discussed and practiced. Moreover, he considers the social and economic aspects of marriage as both a personal relationship and a religious bond, and explores how the Jews of antiquity negotiated the gap between marital realities and their ideals. Focusing on the various experiences of Jews throughout the Mediterranean basin and in Babylonia, Satlow argues that different communities, even rabbinic ones, constructed their own "Jewish" marriage: they read their received traditions and rituals through the lens of a basic understanding of marriage that they shared with their non-Jewish neighbors. He also maintains that Jews idealized marriage in a way that responded to the ideals of their respective societies, mediating between such values as honor and the far messier realities of marital life. Employing Jewish and non-Jewish literary texts, papyri, inscriptions, and material artifacts, Satlow paints a vibrant portrait of ancient Judaism while sharpening and clarifying present discussions on modern marriage for Jews and non-Jews alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aJewish marriage customs and rites. 0aMarriagexHistoryyTo 1500. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / Rituals & Practice.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187495zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187495.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN